    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-01-14T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-01-14T11:00:00-05:00" n="797"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d797">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.2331/53: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Peru</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dearing</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lima</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-01-14T11:00:00-05:00"
                            >January 14, 1936—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 12:45 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>4. Referring to the Embassy’s telegram 2, January 9, 2 p.m.,<note n="20"
                        xml:id="d797fn20">Not printed.</note> Minister of Finance decree of January
                    8th, suspends higher import duties on woolen and cotton textiles from Great
                    Britain until negotiations for Commercial Treaty with England has been
                    approved.</p>
                <pb facs="1008" n="909" xml:id="pg_909"/>
                <p>The decree mentions that the treaty negotiations almost concluded and that action
                    taken is intended to prevent obstacles to favorable termination of this
                    agreement.</p>
                <p>This decree, which the Minister of Finance has ordered not to be made public, is
                    discriminatory and gives competitive advantages to British goods.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Dearing</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
